Long before Turkey’s intention to join the European Union, European powers were burning with the desire to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial effort.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least this is what the guidebooks say.
The building surrounds the end of the platforms, with a tower at each of the front corners, and looks like a German rural town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is a little drudgery.
However, looking at the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious what a large-scale enterprise this was the most western gate.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the “late future” of the conquests, sought to realize its ambitions for the conquest of the Middle East with the help of this railway from Damascus through Baghdad to today’s Saudi Arabia.
The German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
Its railway lines were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabian partisans.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and expelled the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria.
