The collision avoidance "bee car"
In order to develop accident prevention technologies, Nissan is inspired by nature and the world of bees.
The Japanese company designed a robot to avoid accidents by mimicking bees.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in the development of collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technology Center, in collaboration with the renowned University of Tokyo’s Advanced Science and Technology Research Center, built this small robot in Japan.
Kazuhiro Doi, Director of Technology PR and Research Development, said the BR23C is an extension of Nissan’s four-tier safety cover.
The robot enhances the ability to avoid collisions with the company’s products.
While flying, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety cover.
However, the role of the complex eye of the uterus is much more important, with which it can see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees. Consequently, it can fly undisturbed in the personal space of the uterus.
To replicate the function of the complex eye, engineers designed a laser rangefinder.
The instrument identifies obstacles within a range of up to 2 metres in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an action to avoid collision.
"As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot, mimicking the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid collision.
The system is best distinguished by the fact that in this case the avoidance manoeuvre is completely automatic.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the manoeuvring manoeuvre should not be directed upwards or downwards, or diagonally, only in two dimensions, and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels, that is, not in infinite directions and ways, as in the case of bees.
Therefore, apart from acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used a rotation function in the robot to avoid collisions.
“This structure only needs to process data every few seconds and respond to them.
There is no need for data storage or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may sound surprising, but it really isn’t gigabytes, but we don’t even talk about megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of technology for immediate collision prevention, which, according to Nissan’s estimates, could enter mass-produced cars within ten years.
The robot operates with lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, it may be possible to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system in order to get the car to its final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
