Monday's statement by Rafael Correa, Quito
The re-establishment of the republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is a common plan for Venezuelan Hugo Chavez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the pattern of his fellow presidents and friends, Correa explained his ideas about the new constitution.
He successfully completed his mission, as 64% of the voters voted in favour of the referendum, according to official results, which accounted for 80% of the votes.
According to this, 28% of the population voted against, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% were cast as uncompleted.
For the adoption of the draft Constitution, 50% + 1 vote was required.
On Sunday, two polls at the exit of the polling stations and a countdown by a non-governmental organisation both proved the huge advantage of "yes" votes with a 63% and 70% ratio.
Rafael Correa spoke about the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday night.
"The Constitution has won a sweeping victory," he said, thanking the Ecuadorians at the governor's seat in Guayaquil, 280 kilometres southwest of Quito.
As is well known, Rafael Correa congratulated Chávez, Morales and Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.
According to a report by the Organization of American States (OAS), the vote took place in a relaxed atmosphere, with a main theme of 444 points, summarising the principles of "new socialism" defended by the president.
The proposed constitution puts the state power at the service of the economy, maintaining to the state the right to “design development” for a country that is basically living on oil extraction by foreign companies and on foreign currency sent by immigrants.
The draft constitution of Correa, elected in 2006, also strengthens the power of the Head of State, who can obtain a mandate for a maximum of two consecutive periods and is entitled to dissolve the National Assembly.
