Fox in the henhouse
In the United States, life and health insurers, based on people’s drug purchase data, often refuse to sign an insurance contract with the applicant.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescription data in all cases to the consent of the person concerned.
This has to be in an independent hands, otherwise we'll leave the chicken to the fox," said Richard Dicket, the developer of the drug prescription program.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the amount due in the event of damage dependent on the health of the applicant customer, and if the risk is considered too high, they do not make any insurance with it.
In the past, the person was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only with knowledge of the outcome of the examination.
Dick has worked out a much cheaper procedure for ten years: from pharmacies, the customer ID number makes it easy to obtain which drugs he has purchased in the last year and a half, and from this the program itself deduces what kind of disease he is suffering from and what his health condition is.
For example, if you regularly take a high dose of cholesterol, it suggests that your blood fat level is practically unmanageable, which immediately ranks you in a higher risk category.
Several versions of the scheme are in circulation, some of them also set a risk multiplier number, so the insurer has little to do outside of the paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that some drugs can be used for several purposes, for example, some compounds can also be used against migraines or heat waves, but they can also be effective against depression.
The latter is a significant risk-increasing factor for business insurers, the former are not.
Separate companies were formed to retrieve and process the data, and before they obtain the necessary information from the pharmacies, they ask for the patient’s consent.
The authorities are now obliged to do so, although they have not been punished for their failure so far.
More recently, some companies are also processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them with drug consumption data, so they can provide an even more accurate picture of patients’ health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and it will be more and more difficult to monitor usage.
There is a separate Health Data Protection Act, but it covers only healthcare providers and insurers.
Before Congress, there is a bill that also gives the authorities control over companies specialising in data reporting.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough: he has therefore improved his program, which would bind the data to the explicit consent of the data subject.
Another issue is that the data subject can hardly deny the consent, otherwise the insurers will not enter into a contract with him.
So the hens are somewhat dependent on the fox's benevolence.
